{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01W6TMNGcqQ7oSaN2kaTvuFp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: Clause extractor identifies all key terms**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether a real LLM/AI model correctly identifies key terms. The failure mode is whether the extractor *correctly* identifies terms, not about module handoffs.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network dependency beyond the AI call itself.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - does correctness depend on what a real LLM produces? The clause extractor is an \"AI reviewer\" - it's doing classification/extraction from text. Running 100 times might give different results. This is Agentic.\n\n\n- MULTI-STEP: No, just one reviewer step.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic**\n\n**Behavior 2: Risk assessor flags indirect/euphemistic problematic language**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about semantic understanding of indirect language - a quality/correctness question for the AI model.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - this is explicitly about whether the AI model can understand euphemistic language, which is a quality/capability question. Different runs might produce different results. This is Agentic.\n- MULTI-STEP: No, just one reviewer step.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic**\n\n**Behavior 3:** Now I'm looking at the third behavior to apply the same framework.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about AI model correctness in determining compliance - a quality/accuracy question.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - correctness depends on what the real AI model produces. This is Agentic.\n- MULTI-STEP: No, just one reviewer step.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic**\n\n**Behavior 4: Merge step preserves both assessments with attribution when there's conflict**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the merge algorithm's logic when given conflicting inputs - whether it fails when two reviewers disagree. This could be tested with fixed reviewer outputs, so the failure mode is in the merge function itself, not in how modules hand off data.\n- REAL-INFRA: No.\n- LLM-DEP: No - the merge step is deterministic logic that combines inputs.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is Unit-level since I can test the merge logic with predetermined conflicting assessments without needing any LLM involvement.\n\nMinimum level: **Unit**\n\n**Behavior 5: Full pipeline completes correctly for a real contract without losing any individual reviewer's findings**\n\nThis requires the entire workflow - all three reviewers dispatching in sequence, collecting their results, and merging them together. The real AI models are involved, and there are multiple agentic steps chained together.\n\nMinimum level: **Workflow**\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. For the clause extractor, the agentic level dominates since this is fundamentally about AI extraction quality. The risk assessor with euphemistic language detection is even more clearly an agentic capability - the model needs to understand nuanced semantic meaning, so that gets the highest probability. The compliance checker follows a similar pattern where the AI's ability to reason about regulatory requirements is the critical factor.\n\nThe merge step conflict resolution is different - this is mostly deterministic logic with fixed inputs, so the unit level probability is highest, with some integration testing needed to verify how modules pass data between steps. The full pipeline test, though, is primarily a workflow concern since it exercises the multi-step nature of the system, even though individual agentic steps are involved.\n\nNow I'm checking whether each behavior's test description actually matches its classification - B1 and B2 both require real LLM calls, so they're agentic, and B3 should too.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9499,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9499},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cc2b3d17-d171-42c3-a2a8-9b57a51c123a","uuid":"f32b94a0-5a58-4fe0-bc36-1e3f58551726"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01W6TMNGcqQ7oSaN2kaTvuFp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Rf8sWHp5BUyjDMiWBBxJD3","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) in a contract","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is extraction quality — whether the AI model correctly finds and categorizes every key term. This is not a module-handoff bug; it's about what the model produces. LLM-DEP: Correctness depends entirely on real LLM output. A mock would always return whatever we program it to return, hiding real extraction misses. Running 100 times on the same contract may yield different recall rates for subtle terms. REAL-INFRA/MULTI-STEP: No OS/network or multi-step dependency beyond the single AI call.","test_description":"Submit a synthetic legal contract with a known, exhaustive ground-truth set of parties, dates, obligations, and penalty clauses to the real clause extractor. Assert that every ground-truth term appears in the extractor's output with the correct category label. Failure = any ground-truth term missing or miscategorized.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Risk assessor flags indirect or euphemistic problematic language under the configured risk policy","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is semantic reasoning — whether the model recognizes that a euphemism ('mutually agreed adjustment' for an uncapped liability clause) violates policy. A unit test with mocked output proves nothing. LLM-DEP: Whether 'indirect' phrasing is recognized as risky is exactly the kind of judgment that varies across real model runs and cannot be predetermined. Any mock would hard-code the answer, bypassing the entire failure surface. REAL-INFRA/MULTI-STEP: Single reviewer step, no OS/network beyond the AI call.","test_description":"Construct contract snippets where high-risk clauses are phrased euphemistically (e.g., 'reasonable cost adjustment' masking unlimited indemnification). Submit to the real risk assessor with a strict risk policy. Assert each snippet is flagged as high-risk. Failure = euphemistic clause passes unflagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.86,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is regulatory reasoning accuracy — whether the model correctly maps contract language to jurisdiction-specific rules. This is a quality/correctness question for the AI reviewer, not a module-boundary bug. LLM-DEP: Compliance determination requires legal reasoning over jurisdiction-specific regulations. Whether a given clause satisfies GDPR Article 28, for instance, depends on what the real model reasons about the text. Results can vary; mocking bypasses this entirely. REAL-INFRA/MULTI-STEP: Single step, no multi-step or OS dependency.","test_description":"Prepare contracts with known compliance status (one fully compliant, one with a specific regulatory violation) for a target jurisdiction. Feed each to the real compliance checker. Assert the compliant contract passes and the non-compliant contract fails with the correct regulatory citation. Failure = incorrect pass/fail determination.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.87,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Merge step preserves both assessments with attribution when two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is entirely in the merge function's conflict-resolution logic — given two pre-formed reviewer outputs that disagree on the same clause, does the merge preserve both with correct attribution? This is deterministic algorithmic logic, not a module-handoff failure and not LLM-dependent. LLM-DEP: No — we supply fixed, pre-constructed reviewer outputs as inputs; what the real model would produce is irrelevant to testing this specific logic. REAL-INFRA: None. The merge step operates on in-memory data structures. A unit test calling the merge function directly with crafted conflicting inputs is both necessary and sufficient.","test_description":"Construct two reviewer output objects (e.g., extractor result: clause_type='standard', risk_assessor result: clause_type='high_risk') for the same clause ID. Call the merge function directly with these fixed inputs. Assert the merged report contains both assessments, each attributed to its source reviewer, with no assessment dropped or overwritten.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Full pipeline — dispatching to all three reviewers in parallel, collecting results, merging — completes without losing any reviewer's findings","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is about the end-to-end pipeline: parallel dispatch, result collection across all three branches, and merge. Bugs here (e.g., a dropped future, a silent timeout on one reviewer, a merge that silently discards one branch's output) only appear when all steps run together. MULTI-STEP: This requires three real agentic steps running in parallel followed by a merge — a multi-step agentic sequence. LLM-DEP: All three reviewers are real AI models; their outputs must be real to expose collection and merge edge cases caused by actual response shapes. Mocking any reviewer hides whether the pipeline correctly handles real reviewer output formats and latency. A Workflow test is the minimum level that exercises the full failure surface.","test_description":"Run the full pipeline against a real contract document using all three real AI reviewers. After pipeline completion, assert: (a) the unified report contains findings attributed to all three reviewers, (b) no reviewer's output is missing from the merged report, and (c) any clause present in multiple reviewers' outputs appears with all attributions preserved. Failure = any reviewer's findings absent from the final report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.8}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9499,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9499},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cc2b3d17-d171-42c3-a2a8-9b57a51c123a","uuid":"e9cea476-b50d-43fd-960d-01383b157171"}
